verses.text: He called down famine on the land and destroyed all their supplies of food;
and he sent a man before them- Joseph, sold as a slave.
They bruised his feet with shackles, his neck was put in irons,
till what he foretold came to pass, till the word of the LORD proved him true.
The king sent and released him, the ruler of peoples set him free.
He made him master of his household, ruler over all he possessed,
to instruct his princes as he pleased and teach his elders wisdom.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105
rsbNotes.text: Ps. 105 While Ps. 104 praises God’s acts in creating the world, this song meditates on His acts in the world’s continuing history. The first fifteen verses are quoted (along with Ps. 96 and part of 106) in 1 Chr. 16, perhaps indicating use of the psalm in worship.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105:16–22
rsbNotes.text: 105:16–22 God promoted Joseph to a position of power in Egypt.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105:16
rsbNotes.text: 105:16 he summoned. God directed the events in Egypt so that when famine threatened that country Joseph was in power and able to save many people (Gen. 50:20).

verses.text: Then Israel entered Egypt; Jacob lived as an alien in the land of Ham.
The LORD made his people very fruitful; he made them too numerous for their foes,
whose hearts he turned to hate his people, to conspire against his servants.
He sent Moses his servant, and Aaron, whom he had chosen.
They performed his miraculous signs among them, his wonders in the land of Ham.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105:23
rsbNotes.text:
105:23 Israel came to Egypt. See Gen. 46.

the land of Ham. Another name for Egypt.

verses.text: He sent darkness and made the land dark- for had they not rebelled against his words?
He turned their waters into blood, causing their fish to die.
Their land teemed with frogs, which went up into the bedrooms of their rulers.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105:28
rsbNotes.text: 105:28 He sent darkness. The psalmist emphasizes the ninth plague by naming it first.

verses.text: He spoke, and there came swarms of flies, and gnats throughout their country.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105:31
rsbNotes.text: 105:31 flies, and gnats. These are the third and fourth plagues in reverse order of their actual occurrence in Egypt.

verses.text: He turned their rain into hail, with lightning throughout their land;
he struck down their vines and fig trees and shattered the trees of their country.
He spoke, and the locusts came, grasshoppers without number;
they ate up every green thing in their land, ate up the produce of their soil.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105:32
rsbNotes.text: 105:32 hail. The fifth and sixth plagues are unmentioned by the psalmist. The plague of hail was the seventh.

verses.text: Then he struck down all the firstborn in their land, the firstfruits of all their manhood.

rsbNotes.title: Ps 105:36
rsbNotes.text: 105:36 the firstborn. The tenth and final plague, after which Egypt allowed Israel to leave Goshen.
